# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: agda-lang
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:agda-lang/agda-programming-language] Agda is also a proof assistant based on the *propositions-as-types* paradigm (Curry–Howard correspondence), but unlike Rocq, has no separate *tactics* language, and proofs are written in a functional programming style.
[src:agda-lang/agda-programming-language] The language has ordinary programming constructs such as data types, pattern matching, records, let expressions and modules, and a Haskell-like syntax.
[src:agda-lang/agda-programming-language] The system has Emacs, Atom, and VS Code interfaces but can also be run in batch processing mode from a command-line interface.
[src:agda-lang/agda-programming-language] Agda is based on Zhaohui Luo's unified theory of dependent types (UTT), a type theory similar to Martin-Löf type theory.
[src:agda-lang/agda-programming-language] Agda is named after the Swedish song "Hönan Agda", written by Cornelis Vreeswijk, which is about a hen named Agda.
[src:agda-lang/agda-programming-language] This alludes to the name of the theorem prover Rocq, which was originally named Coq after Thierry Coquand.
[src:agda-lang/agda-programming-language] The main way of defining data types in Agda is via inductive data types which are similar to algebraic data types in non-dependently typed programming languages.
[src:agda-lang/agda-programming-language] Basically, it means that there are two ways to construct a value of type $\mathbb {N}$ , representing a natural number.
[src:agda-lang/agda-programming-language] To begin, `zero` is a natural number, and if `n` is a natural number, then `suc n`, standing for the successor of `n`, is a natural number too.
[src:agda-lang/agda-programming-language] The first constructor, `z≤n`, corresponds to the axiom that zero is less than or equal to any natural number.
[src:agda-lang/agda-programming-language] The second constructor, `s≤s`, corresponds to an inference rule, allowing to turn a proof of `n ≤ m` into a proof of `suc n ≤ suc m`.
[src:agda-lang/agda-programming-language] So the value `s≤s {zero} {suc zero} (z≤n {suc zero})` is a proof that one (the successor of zero), is less than or equal to two (the successor of one).
[src:agda-lang/agda-programming-language] The parameters provided in curly brackets may be omitted if they can be inferred.
[src:agda-lang/agda-programming-language] In core type theory, induction and recursion principles are used to prove theorems about inductive types.
[src:agda-lang/agda-programming-language] In Agda, dependently typed pattern matching is used instead.
[src:agda-lang/agda-programming-language] This way of writing recursive functions/inductive proofs is more natural than applying raw induction principles.
[src:agda-lang/agda-programming-language] In Agda, dependently typed pattern matching is a primitive of the language; the core language lacks the induction/recursion principles that pattern matching translates to.
[src:agda-lang/agda-programming-language] One of the distinctive features of Agda, when compared with other similar systems such as Rocq, is heavy reliance on metavariables for program construction.
[src:agda-lang/agda-programming-language] When interacting with the system in Emacs mode, it will show the user the expected type and allow them to refine the metavariable, i.e., to replace it with more detailed code.
[src:agda-lang/agda-programming-language] This feature allows incremental program construction in a way similar to tactics-based proof assistants such as Rocq.
[src:agda-lang/agda-programming-language] Programming in pure type theory involves a lot of tedious and repetitive proofs.
[src:agda-lang/agda-programming-language] Although Agda has no separate tactics language, it is possible to program useful tactics within Agda.
[src:agda-lang/agda-programming-language] Typically, this works by writing an Agda function that optionally returns a proof of some property of interest.
[src:agda-lang/agda-programming-language] (The pattern `()`, called *absurd*, matches if the type checker finds that its type is uninhabited, i.e. proves that it stands for a false proposition, typically because all possible constructors have arguments that are unavailable, i.e. they have unsatisfiable premisses.
[src:agda-lang/agda-programming-language] Here no value of type `isJust A` can be constructed because, in that context, no value of type `A` exists to which we could apply the constructor `Just`.
[src:agda-lang/agda-programming-language] The actual proof of each lemma will be automatically constructed at type-checking time.
[src:agda-lang/agda-programming-language] If the tactic fails, type-checking will fail.
[src:agda-lang/agda-programming-language] Further, to write more complex tactics, Agda supports automation via reflective programming (reflection).
[src:agda-lang/agda-programming-language] The reflection mechanism allows quoting program fragments into, or unquoting them from, the abstract syntax tree.
[src:agda-lang/agda-programming-language] The way reflection is used is similar to the way Template Haskell works.
[src:agda-lang/agda-programming-language] Another mechanism for proof automation is proof search action in Emacs mode.
[src:agda-lang/agda-programming-language] It enumerates possible proof terms (limited to 5 seconds), and if one of the terms fits the specification, it will be put in the meta variable where the action is invoked.
[src:agda-lang/agda-programming-language] This action accepts hints, e.g., which theorems and from which modules can be used, whether the action can use pattern matching, etc.
[src:agda-lang/agda-programming-language] Agda is a total functional programming language, i.e., each program in it must terminate and all possible patterns must be matched.
[src:agda-lang/agda-programming-language] Without this feature, the logic behind the language becomes inconsistent, and it becomes possible to prove arbitrary statements.
[src:agda-lang/agda-programming-language] For termination checking, Agda uses the approach of the Foetus termination checker.
[src:agda-lang/agda-programming-language] Agda has an extensive de facto standard library, which includes many useful definitions and theorems about basic data structures, such as natural numbers, lists, and vectors.
[src:agda-lang/agda-programming-language] The library is in beta, and is under active development.
[src:agda-lang/agda-programming-language] One of the more notable features of Agda is a heavy reliance on Unicode in program source code.
[src:agda-lang/agda-programming-language] The standard Emacs mode uses shortcuts for input, such as `\Sigma` for Σ.
[src:agda-lang/agda-programming-language] There are two compiler backends, MAlonzo for Haskell and one for JavaScript.
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] In computer science and logic, a **dependent type** is a type whose definition depends on a value.
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] It is an overlapping feature of type theory and type systems.
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] In intuitionistic type theory, dependent types are used to encode logic's quantifiers like "for all" and "there exists".
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] In functional programming languages like Agda, ATS, Rocq (previously known as *Coq*), F*, Epigram, Idris, and Lean, dependent types help reduce bugs by enabling the programmer to assign types that further restrain the set of possible implementations.
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] Two common examples of dependent types are *dependent functions* and *dependent pairs*.
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] The return type of a dependent function may depend on the *value* (not just type) of one of its arguments.
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] For instance, a function that takes a positive integer n may return an array of length n , where the array length is part of the type of the array.
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] (Note that this is different from polymorphism and generic programming, both of which include the type as an argument.) A dependent pair may have a second value, the type of which depends on the first value.
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] Sticking with the array example, a dependent pair may be used to pair an array with its length in a type-safe way.
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] Dependent types add complexity to a type system.
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] Deciding the equality of dependent types in a program may require computations.
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] In 1934, Haskell Curry noticed that the types used in typed lambda calculus, and in its combinatory logic counterpart, followed the same pattern as axioms in propositional logic.
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] Going further, for every proof in the logic, there was a matching function (term) in the programming language.
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] One of Curry's examples was the correspondence between simply typed lambda calculus and intuitionistic logic.
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] Predicate logic is an extension of propositional logic, adding quantifiers.
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] Howard and de Bruijn extended lambda calculus to match this more powerful logic by creating types for dependent functions, which correspond to "for all", and dependent pairs, which correspond to "there exists".
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] Because of this, and other work by Howard, propositions-as-types is known as the Curry–Howard correspondence.
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] In dependent type theory, a dependent type is a type whose specification may vary with a value, and can be viewed as analogous to an indexed family of sets.
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] Let ${\mathcal {U}}$ denote a universe of types, and write $A:{\mathcal {U}}$ to indicate that A is a type in ${\mathcal {U}}$ .
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] A dependent **family of types** over A is written $B:A\to {\mathcal {U}}$ , meaning that to each term $a:A$ the family assigns a type $B(a):{\mathcal {U}}$ .
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] Thus, given $A:{\mathcal {U}}$ and $B:A\to {\mathcal {U}}$ , the expression $B(a)$ denotes a type that depends on the particular value a .
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] In standard terminology, this is described by saying that the type $B(a)$ varies with a .
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] A function whose type of return value varies with its argument (i.e. there is no fixed codomain) is a **dependent function** and the type of this function is called **dependent product type**, **pi-type** (**Π type**) or **dependent function type**.
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] From a family of types $B:A\to {\mathcal {U}}$ we may construct the type of dependent functions ${\textstyle \prod _{x:A}B(x)}$ , whose terms are functions that take a term $a:A$ and return a term in $B(a)$ .
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] For this example, the dependent function type is typically written as ${\textstyle \prod _{x:A}B(x)}$ or ${\textstyle \prod {(x:A)}B(x)}$ .
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] If $B:A\to {\mathcal {U}}$ is a constant function, the corresponding dependent product type is equivalent to an ordinary function type.
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] That is, ${\textstyle \prod _{x:A}B}$ is judgmentally equal to $A\to B$ when B does not depend on x .
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] The name 'Π-type' comes from the idea that these may be viewed as a Cartesian product of types. Π-types can also be understood as models of universal quantifiers.
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] For example, if we write $\operatorname {Vec} (\mathbb {R} ,n)$ for *n*-tuples of real numbers, then ${\textstyle \prod _{n:\mathbb {N} }\operatorname {Vec} (\mathbb {R} ,n)}$ would be the type of a function which, given a natural number n, returns a tuple of real numbers of size n.
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] The usual function space arises as a special case when the range type does not actually depend on the input.
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] E.g. ${\textstyle \prod _{n:\mathbb {N} }{\mathbb {R} }}$ is the type of functions from natural numbers to the real numbers, which is written as $\mathbb {N} \to \mathbb {R}$ in typed lambda calculus.
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] The dual of the dependent product type is the **dependent pair type**, **dependent sum type**, **sigma-type**, or (confusingly) **dependent product type**.
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] Sigma-types can also be understood as existential quantifiers.
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] Continuing the above example, if, in the universe of types ${\mathcal {U}}$ , there is a type $A:{\mathcal {U}}$ and a family of types $B:A\to {\mathcal {U}}$ , then there is a dependent pair type ${\textstyle \sum _{x:A}B(x)}$ .
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] The dependent pair type captures the idea of an ordered pair where the type of the second term is dependent on the value of the first.
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] If B is a constant function, then the dependent pair type becomes (is judgmentally equal to) the product type, that is, an ordinary Cartesian product $A\times B$ .
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] For a more concrete example, taking A to again be type of unsigned integers from 0 to 255, and $B(a)$ to again be equal to $X_{a}$ for 256 more arbitrary $X_{a}$ , then ${\textstyle \sum _{x:A}B(x)}$ devolves into the sum $X_{0}+X_{1}+X_{2}+\ldots +X_{253}+X_{254}+X_{255}$ .
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] Let $A:{\mathcal {U}}$ be some type, and let $B:A\to {\mathcal {U}}$ .
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] By the Curry–Howard correspondence, B can be interpreted as a logical predicate on terms of A .
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] For a given $a:A$ , whether the type $B(a)$ is inhabited indicates whether a satisfies this predicate.
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] The correspondence can be extended to existential quantification and dependent pairs: the proposition $\exists {a}{\in }A\,B(a)$ is true if and only if the type ${\textstyle \sum _{a:A}B(a)}$ is inhabited.
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] For example, $m:\mathbb {N}$ is less than or equal to $n:\mathbb {N}$ if and only if there exists another natural number $k:\mathbb {N}$ such that $m+k=n$ .
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] That is, a proof of the statement that m is less than or equal to n is a pair that contains both a non-negative number k , which is the difference between m and n , and a proof of the equality $m+k=n$ .
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] Henk Barendregt developed the lambda cube as a means of classifying type systems along three axes.
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] The eight corners of the resulting cube-shaped diagram each correspond to a type system, with simply typed lambda calculus in the least expressive corner, and calculus of constructions in the most expressive.
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] The three axes of the cube correspond to three different augmentations of the simply typed lambda calculus: the addition of dependent types, the addition of polymorphism, and the addition of higher kinded type constructors (functions from types to types, for example).
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] The lambda cube is generalized further by pure type systems.
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] The system $\lambda \Pi$ of pure first order dependent types, corresponding to the logical framework LF, is obtained by generalising the function space type of the simply typed lambda calculus to the dependent product type.
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] The system $\lambda \Pi 2$ of second order dependent types is obtained from $\lambda \Pi$ by allowing quantification over type constructors.
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] In this theory the dependent product operator subsumes both the $\to$ operator of simply typed lambda calculus and the $\forall$ binder of System F.
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] The higher order system $\lambda \Pi \omega$ extends $\lambda \Pi 2$ to all four forms of abstraction from the lambda cube: functions from terms to terms, types to types, terms to types and types to terms.
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] The system corresponds to the calculus of constructions whose derivative, the calculus of inductive constructions is the underlying system of Rocq.
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] The Curry–Howard correspondence implies that types can be constructed that express arbitrarily complex mathematical properties.
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] If the user can supply a constructive proof that a type is *inhabited* (i.e., that a value of that type exists) then a compiler can check the proof and convert it into executable computer code that computes the value by carrying out the construction.
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] The proof checking feature makes dependently typed languages closely related to proof assistants.
[src:agda-lang/dependent-type] The code-generation aspect provides a powerful approach to formal program verification and proof-carrying code, since the code is derived directly from a mechanically verified mathematical proof.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Martin-Löf designed the type theory on the principles of mathematical constructivism.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Constructivism requires any existence proof to contain a "witness".
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] So, any proof of "there exists a prime greater than 1000" must identify a specific number that is both prime and greater than 1000.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Intuitionistic type theory accomplished this design goal by internalizing the BHK interpretation.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] A useful consequence is that proofs become mathematical objects that can be examined, compared, and manipulated.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Intuitionistic type theory's type constructors were built to follow a one-to-one correspondence with logical connectives.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] For example, the logical connective called implication ( $A\implies B$ ) corresponds to the type of a function ( $A\to B$ ).
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] This correspondence is called the Curry–Howard isomorphism.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Prior type theories had also followed this isomorphism, but Martin-Löf's was the first to extend it to predicate logic by introducing dependent types.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] A type theory is a kind of mathematical ontology, or foundation, describing the fundamental objects that exist.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] In the standard foundation, set theory combined with mathematical logic, the fundamental object is the set, which is a container that contains elements.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] In type theory, the fundamental object is the term, each of which belongs to one and only one type.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Intuitionistic type theory has three finite types, which are then composed using five different type constructors.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Unlike set theories, type theories are not built on top of a logic like Frege's.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] So, each feature of the type theory does double duty as a feature of both math and logic.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] There are three finite types: The **0** type contains no terms.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] The **1** type contains one canonical term.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] The **2** type contains two canonical terms.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Because the **0** type contains no terms, it is also called the empty type.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] It is used to represent anything that cannot exist.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] It is also written $\bot$ and represents anything unprovable (that is, a proof of it cannot exist).
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] As a result, negation is defined as a function to it: $\neg A:=A\to \bot$ .
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Likewise, the **1** type contains one canonical term and represents existence.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Finally, the **2** type contains two canonical terms.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] It represents a definite choice between two values.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] It is used for Boolean values but *not* propositions.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Propositions are instead represented by particular types.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] For instance, a true proposition can be represented by the **1** type, while a false proposition can be represented by the **0** type.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] But we cannot assert that these are the only propositions, i.e. the law of excluded middle does not hold for propositions in intuitionistic type theory.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] As with typical ordered pair (or 2-tuple) types, a Σ-type can describe the Cartesian product, $A\times B$ , of two other types, A and B .
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Logically, such an ordered pair would hold a proof of A and a proof of B , so one may see such a type written as $A\wedge B$ .
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Σ-types are more powerful than typical ordered pair types because of dependent typing.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] In the ordered pair, the type of the second term can depend on the value of the first term.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] For example, the first term of the pair might be a natural number and the second term's type might be a sequence of reals of length equal to the first term.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Using set-theory terminology, this is similar to an indexed disjoint union of sets.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] In the case of the usual cartesian product, the type of the second term does not depend on the value of the first term.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] The value of the first term, n , is not dependent on the type of the second term, ${\mathbb {R} }$ .
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Σ-types can be used to build up longer dependently-typed tuples used in mathematics and the records or structs used in most programming languages.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Dependent typing allows Σ-types to serve the role of existential quantifier.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] The statement "there exists an n of type ${\mathbb {N} }$ , such that $P(n)$ is proven" becomes the type of ordered pairs where the first item is the value n of type ${\mathbb {N} }$ and the second item is a proof of $P(n)$ .
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Notice that the type of the second item (proofs of $P(n)$ ) depends on the value in the first part of the ordered pair ( n ).
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] As with typical function types, they consist of an input type and an output type.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] They are more powerful than typical function types however, in that the return type can depend on the input value.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Functions in type theory are different from set theory.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] In set theory, you look up the argument's value in a set of ordered pairs.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] In type theory, the argument is substituted into a term and then computation ("reduction") is applied to the term.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] When the output type does not depend on the input value, the function type is often simply written with a $\to$ .
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Thus, ${\mathbb {N} }\to {\mathbb {R} }$ is the type of functions from natural numbers to real numbers.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Such Π-types correspond to logical implication.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] The logical proposition $A\implies B$ corresponds to the type $A\to B$ , containing functions that take proofs-of-A and return proofs-of-B.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Π-types are also used in logic for universal quantification.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] The statement "for every n of type ${\mathbb {N} }$ , $P(n)$ is proven" becomes a function from n of type ${\mathbb {N} }$ to proofs of $P(n)$ .
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Thus, given the value for n the function generates a proof that $P(\,\cdot \,)$ holds for that value.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Given two terms like $2+2$ and $2\cdot 2$ , you can create a new type $2+2=2\cdot 2$ .
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] The terms of that new type represent proofs that the pair reduce to the same canonical term.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Thus, since both $2+2$ and $2\cdot 2$ compute to the canonical term 4 , there will be a term of the type $2+2=2\cdot 2$ .
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] It is possible to create =-types such as $1=2$ where the terms do not reduce to the same canonical term, but you will be unable to create terms of that new type.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] In fact, if you were able to create a term of $1=2$ , you could create a term of $\bot$ .
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Putting that into a function would generate a function of type $1=2\to \bot$ .
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Since $\ldots \to \bot$ is how intuitionistic type theory defines negation, you would have $\neg (1=2)$ or, finally, $1\neq 2$ .
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Equality of proofs is an area of active research in proof theory and has led to the development of homotopy type theory and other type theories.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Inductive types allow the creation of complex, self-referential types.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] For example, a linked list of natural numbers is either an empty list or a pair of a natural number and another linked list.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Inductive types can be used to define unbounded mathematical structures like trees, graphs, etc..
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] In fact, the natural numbers type may be defined as an inductive type, either being 0 or the successor of another natural number.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Inductive types define new constants, such as zero $0{\mathbin {:}}{\mathbb {N} }$ and the successor function $S{\mathbin {:}}{\mathbb {N} }\to {\mathbb {N} }$ .
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Since S does not have a definition and cannot be evaluated using substitution, terms like $S0$ and $SSS0$ become the canonical terms of the natural numbers.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Proofs on inductive types are made possible by induction.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Each new inductive type comes with its own inductive rule.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Inductive types in intuitionistic type theory are defined in terms of W-types, the type of well-founded trees.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Later work in type theory generated coinductive types, induction-recursion, and induction-induction for working on types with more obscure kinds of self-referentiality.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Higher inductive types allow equality to be defined between terms.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] The universe types allow proofs to be written about all the types created with the other type constructors.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Every term in the universe type ${\mathcal {U}}_{0}$ can be mapped to a type created with any combination of $0,1,2,\Sigma ,\Pi ,=,$ and the inductive type constructor.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] However, to avoid paradoxes, there is no term in ${\mathcal {U}}_{n}$ that maps to ${\mathcal {U}}_{n}$ for any ${\mathcal {n}}\in \mathbb {N}$ .
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] To write proofs about all "the small types" and ${\mathcal {U}}_{0}$ , you must use ${\mathcal {U}}_{1}$ , which does contain a term for ${\mathcal {U}}_{0}$ , but not for itself ${\mathcal {U}}_{1}$ .
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] There is a predicative hierarchy of universes, so to quantify a proof over any fixed constant k universes, you can use ${\mathcal {U}}_{k+1}$ .
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Universe types are a tricky feature of type theories.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Martin-Löf's original type theory had to be changed to account for Girard's paradox.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Later research covered topics such as "super universes", "Mahlo universes", and impredicative universes.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] The formal definition of intuitionistic type theory is written using judgements.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] For example, in the statement "if A is a type and B is a type then $\textstyle \sum _{a:A}B$ is a type" there are judgements of "is a type", "and", and "if ... then ...".
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] The expression $\textstyle \sum _{a:A}B$ is not a judgement; it is the type being defined.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] This second level of the type theory can be confusing, particularly where it comes to equality.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] There is a judgement of term equality, which might say $4=2+2$ .
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] It is a statement that two terms reduce to the same canonical term.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] There is also a judgement of type equality, say that $A=B$ , which means every element of A is an element of the type B and vice versa.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] At the type level, there is a type $4=2+2$ and it contains terms if there is a proof that 4 and $2+2$ reduce to the same value.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] (Terms of this type are generated using the term-equality judgement.) Lastly, there is an English-language level of equality, because we use the word "four" and symbol " 4 " to refer to the canonical term $SSSS0$ .
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Synonyms like these are called "definitionally equal" by Martin-Löf.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] The description of judgements below is based on the discussion in Nordström, Petersson, and Smith.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] The formal theory works with *types* and *objects*.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] An object that depends on an object from another type can be done two ways.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] The object-depending-on-object can also be declared as a constant as part of a recursive type.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Here, S is a constant object-depending-on-object.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] It is not associated with an abstraction.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Constants like S can be removed by defining equality.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] S is manipulated as an opaque constant - it has no internal structure for substitution.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] So, objects and types and these relations are used to express formulae in the theory.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] By convention, there is a type that represents all other types.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] It is called ${\mathcal {U}}$ (or $\operatorname {Set}$ ).
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Since ${\mathcal {U}}$ is a type, the members of it are objects.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] There is a dependent type $\operatorname {El}$ that maps each object to its corresponding type.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] *In most texts $\operatorname {El}$ is never written.* From the context of the statement, a reader can almost always tell whether A refers to a type, or whether it refers to the object in ${\mathcal {U}}$ that corresponds to the type.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] This is the complete foundation of the theory.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] To implement logic, each proposition is given its own type.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] The objects in those types represent the different possible ways to prove the proposition.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] If there is no proof for the proposition, then the type has no objects in it.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Operators like "and" and "or" that work on propositions introduce new types and new objects.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] So $A\times B$ is a type that depends on the type A and the type B .
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] The objects in that dependent type are defined to exist for every pair of objects in A and B .
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] If either A or B have no proof and is an empty type, then the new type representing $A\times B$ is also empty.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] This can be done for other types (booleans, natural numbers, etc.) and their operators.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Using the language of category theory, R.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Seely introduced the notion of a locally cartesian closed category (LCCC) as the basic model of type theory.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] This has been refined by Hofmann and Dybjer to Categories with Families or *Categories with Attributes* based on earlier work by Cartmell.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] A fundamental distinction is extensional vs intensional type theory.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] In extensional type theory, definitional (i.e., computational) equality is not distinguished from propositional equality, which requires proof.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] As a consequence type checking becomes undecidable in extensional type theory because programs in the theory might not terminate.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] For example, such a theory allows one to give a type to the Y-combinator; a detailed example of this can be found in Nordstöm and Petersson *Programming in Martin-Löf's Type Theory*.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] However, this does not prevent extensional type theory from being a basis for a practical tool; for example, Nuprl is based on extensional type theory.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] In contrast, in intensional type theory type checking is decidable, but the representation of standard mathematical concepts is somewhat more cumbersome, since intensional reasoning requires using setoids or similar constructions.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] There are many common mathematical objects that are hard to work with or cannot be represented without this, for example, integer numbers, rational numbers, and real numbers.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Integers and rational numbers can be represented without setoids, but this representation is difficult to work with.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Cauchy real numbers cannot be represented without this.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Homotopy type theory works on resolving this problem.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] It allows one to define higher inductive types, which not only define first-order constructors (values or points), but higher-order constructors, i.e. equalities between elements (paths), equalities between equalities (homotopies), *ad infinitum*.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Different forms of type theory have been implemented as the formal systems underlying a number of proof assistants.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] While many are based on Per Martin-Löf's ideas, many have added features, more axioms, or a different philosophical background.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] For instance, the Nuprl system is based on computational type theory and Rocq is based on the calculus of (co)inductive constructions.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Dependent types also feature in the design of programming languages such as ATS, Cayenne, Epigram, Agda, and Idris.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] Per Martin-Löf constructed several type theories that were published at various times, some of them much later than when the preprints with their description became accessible to specialists (among others Jean-Yves Girard and Giovanni Sambin).
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] The list below attempts to list all the theories that have been described in a printed form and to sketch the key features that distinguished them from each other.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] All of these theories had dependent products, dependent sums, disjoint unions, finite types and natural numbers.
[src:agda-lang/intuitionistic-type-theory] All the theories had the same reduction rules that did not include η-reduction either for dependent products or for dependent sums, except for MLTT79 where the η-reduction for dependent products is added.
